\textbf{2.3.1 Elliptic Curve Definition}

An elliptic curve is represented by the following equation:

\emph{y}2= \emph{x}3+ \emph{ax} + \emph{b}

where \emph{a, b} are elements within a finite field F\emph{p}, with
\emph{p} being a prime number that is greater than 3. Furthermore, the
quantity 4\emph{a}3+ 27\emph{b}2must not be divisible by \emph{p}.

\textbf{2.3.2 Point Addition}

The set of points that lie along an elliptic curve, together with a
point at infinity, creates an abelian group whose operation is point
addition. For two points that are included within the elliptic curve,
the point that is created as a result of adding the two points together
includes coordinates that are defined according to the following
equations:

