In elliptic curve cryptography, one of the problems that must be solved
is the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP):

\textbf{Definition 2.1.} \emph{Let P and Q be two points that are
defined within an elliptic curve. The elliptic curve discrete logarithm
problem is the problem of determining the integer k such that Q} =
\emph{kP.}

The elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem is considered to be a
difficult problem to solve within classical computing algorithms; the
best-known algorithms require on the order of\emph{√n} operations to
solve the discrete logarithm problem in elliptic curves, where \emph{n}
is the order of the elliptic curve group.

4

\textbf{2.4} \textbf{The Discrete Logarithm Problem}

In the finite field F\emph{p}, where \emph{p} is a prime number, let
\emph{G} be the multiplicative group whose elements have order \emph{n},
where \emph{n} is a divisor of \emph{p −}1. Additionally, let \emph{g}
be a generator for that group.

\textbf{Definition 2.2.} \emph{Let G be a finite cyclic group of order n
with a generator g. The discrete logarithm problem is, given an element
h within G, to determine the integer x such that gx}= \emph{h.}

Discrete logarithms problems are utilized within cryptographic systems
such as the Diffie-Hellman and ElGamal systems.

