The most common algorithm for factoring integers (known as Shor's
algorithm) can factor any integer in time \emph{O}((log \emph{N})3).
Thus, the algorithm is based upon the use of quantum

5

Fourier transforms to perform the factorization. The algorithm is
performed according to the following steps:

\begin{quote}
1. Choose a random integer \emph{a} within the range of integers between
1 and \emph{N −}1 (inclusive) such that gcd(\emph{a, N}) = 1.

2. Determine the period \emph{r} of the function \emph{f}(\emph{x}) =
\emph{ax}(mod \emph{N}) with the use of quantum Fourier transforms.

3. If the calculated value for \emph{r} is even, and if the value of
\emph{ar/}2is not congruent to -1 (mod \emph{N}), calculate the integers
gcd(\emph{ar/}2+ 1\emph{, N}) and gcd(\emph{ar/}2\emph{−}1\emph{, N}).
Each of these integers will be a factor of the original number \emph{N}.
\end{quote}

\textbf{3.2.2 Mathematical Foundation}

The algorithm relies upon the fact that factoring integers can be
reduced to the problem of determining the period of a function. Thus,
within the quantum computer, quantum Fourier transforms are utilized to
determine that period. For integer \emph{N}, choose a value for \emph{Q}
as 2\emph{q} where the value of \emph{N}2is less than or equal to
\emph{Q} and is less than 2\emph{N}2.

\begin{quote}
The initial state of the quantum computer is the state:
\end{quote}

