Measure the first register again. The value of the measurement will be
the value of the period \emph{r}.

\textbf{3.2.3 Complexity}

The complexity of classical integer factoring algorithms is generally of
the order exp((log \emph{n})1\emph{/}3(log log \emph{n})2\emph{/}3). The
complexity of Shor's quantum factoring algorithm is \emph{O}((log
\emph{n})3).

\textbf{3.3} \textbf{Elliptic Curve Cryptography}

In addition to the factoring problem, Shor's algorithm can also be used
to solve the discrete logarithm problem on elliptic curves. Thus, the
elliptic curve cryptosystems that rely upon the difficulty of solving
such a discrete logarithm problem can also be broken by a quantum
computer that utilizes Shor's algorithm to solve the problem (Shor,
1997). Thus, the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem can be solved
in time \emph{O}((log \emph{n})3), where \emph{n} is the order of the
elliptic curve group.

6

\textbf{4 Quantum-Resistant Cryptographic Mathematics}

\textbf{4.1} \textbf{Lattice Theory Foundations}

\textbf{Definition 4.1} (Lattice)\textbf{.} \emph{A lattice within}
R\emph{nis a discrete subgroup that is generated by a set of n linearly
independent vectors within the same space.}

\emph{n} linearly independent basis vectors within that lattice. Thus,
the lattice consisting of all Thus, a lattice \emph{L} can be
represented as a set of all of the linear combinations of the

linear combinations of \emph{n} linearly independent basis vectors
\emph{b}1\emph{, b}2\emph{, ..., bn} is represented as:

\begin{quote}
\emph{n}\\
\emph{L} = \emph{\{ i}=1 \emph{zibi \textbar{} zi ∈}Z\emph{\}}
\end{quote}

The matrix that is constructed from the linear combination of the basis
vectors within the lattice is referred to as the basis matrix of that
lattice.

\textbf{4.1.1 Fundamental Lattice Problems}

\textbf{Definition 4.2} (Shortest Vector Problem (SVP))\textbf{.}
\emph{Given a lattice within} R\emph{n, find the non-zero vector within
that lattice whose length is the shortest.}

\textbf{Definition 4.3} (Closest Vector Problem (CVP))\textbf{.}
\emph{Given a lattice within} R\emph{n, and a target vector in that same
space, find the vector within the lattice whose distance to the target
vector is the shortest.}

The Shortest Vector Problem (SVP) has been proven to be an NP-hard
problem in classical computation {[}1{]}. Furthermore, no known
algorithm for solving the SVP has been proven to be solvable in
polynomial time by a quantum computer.

\textbf{4.2} \textbf{Learning With Errors (LWE) Problem}

\textbf{4.2.1 Problem Definition}

\textbf{Definition 4.4.} \emph{Let n, q be positive integers, and let χ
be some distribution of values over the integers modulo q. Furthermore,
let s be a vector that is secret to the sender and receiver of some
information. The Learning With Errors (LWE) problem is the problem of
generating a distribution of pairs} (\emph{a, b}) \emph{where a is a
vector of n dimensions whose entries are elements of} Z\emph{q, and
where b is the inner product of a and s (the sum of the products of each
component of a and s) plus some error e whose distribution is
represented by the distribution χ. Fur-thermore, the Search-LWE problem
is the problem of finding s given enough samples of the distribution of
pairs} (\emph{a, b})\emph{. Finally, the Decision-LWE problem is the
problem of recognizing samples of the distribution of pairs} (\emph{a,
b}) \emph{generated using the Search-LWE distribution from
randomly-sampled pairs} (\emph{a, b}) \emph{from the distribution}
Z\emph{n q×} Z\emph{q.}

7

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{4.2.2}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Error Distribution}
\end{quote}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
\multicolumn{2}{@{}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{1.0000} + 2\tabcolsep}@{}}{%
\begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
One of the most common choices of distribution for the error \emph{e} in
the LWE problem is the discrete Gaussian distribution
\emph{D}Z\emph{,σ}. The discrete Gaussian distribution has a probability
distribution function of:

\begin{quote}
\emph{D}Z\emph{,σ}(\emph{x}) = exp(\emph{−πx}2\emph{/σ}2)\\
\emph{z∈}Zexp(\emph{−πz}2\emph{/σ}2)
\end{quote}\strut
\end{minipage}} \\
\textbf{4.3} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Security Reduction: LWE to Lattice Problems}
\end{quote}
\end{minipage} \\
\multicolumn{2}{@{}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{1.0000} + 2\tabcolsep}@{}}{%
\textbf{Theorem 4.1.} \emph{Let n, q be positive integers such that q is
a prime number and q is greater than or equal to} 2\emph{√n.
Furthermore, let α be some positive decimal that is less than 1 such
that αq is greater than or equal to} 2\emph{√n. Then, if there is an
algorithm that can solve the}

\emph{Decision-LWE problem with non-negligible probability relative to
the size of its inputs, there}

\emph{is an algorithm that can solve worst-case instances of the lattice
problems GapSV P} ˜\emph{O}(\emph{n/α})\emph{and}

\emph{SIV P} ˜\emph{O}(\emph{n/α})\emph{{[}8{]}.}} \\
\textbf{4.4} & \begin{minipage}[t]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Ring-LWE}
\end{quote}
\end{minipage} \\
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

Ring-LWE (Learning With Errors over Rings) was developed as a means of
improving the efficiency of the LWE problem. Thus, Ring-LWE shares many
of the same features as the LWE problem (both in form and function), but
has a structure that permits for it to be implemented more efficiently
than the original LWE problem.

\textbf{Definition 4.5} (Ring-LWE)\textbf{.} \emph{Let R be the set of
polynomials of degree less than n with integer coefficients, denoted as}
Z{[}\emph{x}{]}\emph{/}(\emph{xn}+ 1)\emph{. Furthermore, let Rq be the
set of polynomials in R whose coefficients are elements of} Z\emph{q:
Rq} = \emph{R/q}Z{[}\emph{x}{]}\emph{. Ring-LWE is defined in the same
way as the LWE problem, but within this ring Rq: samples of the form}
(\emph{a, b}) \emph{where a is within Rq, b is the inner product of a
and some secret vector s within the ring Rq, and some error distributed
according to the error distribution over the ring R.}

Ring-LWE has been proven to offer significant improvements to the
efficiency of the algorithm relative to LWE while maintaining the same
security guarantees of LWE.

\textbf{4.5} \textbf{Module-LWE}

Module-LWE is a generalization of both the LWE and the Ring-LWE
algorithms.

\textbf{Definition 4.6} (Module-LWE)\textbf{.} \emph{Let Rq be the set
of polynomials of degree less than n with coefficients in} Z\emph{q: Rq}
= Z\emph{q}{[}\emph{x}{]}\emph{/}(\emph{xn}+ 1)\emph{. Furthermore, let
d be any positive integer that is greater than 1. Then Module-LWE can be
defined as a distribution of samples of the form} (\emph{a, b})
\emph{wherein a is within Rd q, the set of d-dimensional vectors whose
entries are elements of Rd q, s is a secret vector within Rd q, and the
error between the inner product of a and s is distributed according to
the error distribution over the ring R.}

Module-LWE provides a generalization of both the LWE and Ring-LWE
algorithms that permits for a balance to be struck between security and
efficiency of the algorithms.

8

