Table 1 presents a comparison of the classical and quantum-resistant
cryptographic systems. The classical systems, such as RSA and ECDSA,
rely upon the structure of cyclic groups and the difficulty of the
discrete logarithm problem within those groups. The quantum-resistant
systems, such as the lattice-based algorithms, utilize
\emph{n}-dimensional lattices instead.

\textbf{5.2} \textbf{Why Quantum Algorithms Fail on Lattices}

\textbf{5.2.1 Absence of Periodicity}

Shor's algorithm finds the period of the function:

\begin{quote}
\emph{f}(\emph{x}) = \emph{ax} (mod \emph{N})
\end{quote}

where \emph{ar≡}1 (mod \emph{N}) for some value of \emph{r}. No such
period exists for problems like the Learning with Errors problem:

\begin{quote}
\emph{f}(\emph{a}) = \emph{⟨a, s⟩}+ \emph{e} (mod \emph{q})
\end{quote}

\textbf{5.2.2 Worst-Case to Average-Case Reduction}

While classical cryptographic algorithms are based upon problems that
are difficult to solve on average, lattice problems are difficult in the
worst case. However, there is a proof that if someone can find an
efficient algorithm for solving the average case of the problem, then
that same algorithm can be used to solve the worst case instance of the
same problem for any lattice.

\textbf{Theorem 5.1} (Worst-Case Hardness)\textbf{.} \emph{Suppose an
attacker can solve instances of the average-case Learning With Errors
problem with probability \textgreater{}}\uline{1 2}+\emph{ϵ for some
constant ϵ \textgreater{}} 0\emph{. Then the same algorithm can solve
instances of the worst-case GapSVP problem with approximation factor γ}
= \emph{O}(\emph{\uline{n}α})\emph{.}

\begin{quote}
The function ˜\emph{O}(\emph{·}) hides factors that are polynomial in
\emph{n}.
\end{quote}

