\textbf{6 Post-Quantum Cryptography Standards}\\
\textbf{6.1} \textbf{NIST Standardization Process}\\
The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is creating
cryptographic stan-dards that are secure from attacks by quantum
computers. The process began in 2016 with the goal of having the
standards published by 2024 {[}6{]}.

\textbf{6.2} \textbf{Selected Algorithms}\\
\textbf{6.2.1} \textbf{CRYSTALS-Kyber (FIPS 203)}\\
CRYSTALS-Kyber (standardized by NIST as ML-KEM) is a KEM whose security
is based upon the Module-LWE problem. This system uses the following
parameters:\\
• \emph{n} = 256\\
• \emph{q} = 3329\\
• \emph{k ∈\{}2\emph{,} 3\emph{,} 4\emph{\}}\\
The process for key generation is as follows:\\
1. Sample a matrix \emph{A} of size \emph{k × k} with elements uniformly
distributed in Z\emph{q}\\
2. Sample a secret vector \emph{s} of size \emph{n} with entries sampled
from a centered binomial distribution\\
3. Sample a vector \emph{e} of size \emph{n} with entries sampled from a
centered binomial distribution 4. Calculate \emph{t} = \emph{As} +
\emph{e} (mod \emph{q}).

The public key is (\emph{A, t}) and the shared secret key is \emph{s}.

10

\textbf{6.2.2 CRYSTALS-Dilithium (FIPS 204)}

CRYSTALS-Dilithium is a digital signature system whose security is based
upon the Module-LWE problem. For each signature:

\begin{quote}
1. Sample a random value \emph{y}.

2. Calculate \emph{w} = \emph{Ay}.

3. Calculate the challenge value \emph{c} = \emph{H}(\emph{w, M}) where
\emph{H} is a cryptographic hash function and \emph{M} is the message
being signed.

4. Calculate the signature \emph{z} = \emph{y} + \emph{cs}.

5. If the sizes of \emph{z} or \emph{w −ct} are outside some pre-defined
bounds, repeat steps 1-3 until the signature is accepted.
\end{quote}

\textbf{6.2.3 FALCON (FIPS 205)}

FALCON is another digital signature system. However, unlike the others
based upon the Module-LWE problem, FALCON uses the NTRU lattice problem
and the GPV framework for digital signatures. Fast Fourier sampling is
used in its creation of the digital signatures.

\textbf{6.3} \textbf{Security Levels}

The standards provide for three security levels, each of which is
roughly equivalent to a certain level of security in classical
cryptography:

\begin{quote}
• Level 1: AES-128 (approximately 143 quantum bits)

• Level 3: AES-192 (approximately 207 quantum bits)

• Level 5: AES-256 (approximately 272 quantum bits)
\end{quote}

\textbf{7 Implications for Blockchain and Cryptocurrency}

\textbf{7.1} \textbf{Current Cryptographic Infrastructure}

\textbf{7.1.1 Bitcoin}

Bitcoin uses the ECDSA algorithm with the secp256k1 elliptic curve for
digital signatures. Given the public key (\emph{P}) and the private key
(\emph{d}), the signature for a message (\emph{m}) is created with the
following equations:

