where \emph{k} is a random value, \emph{G} is a generator for the
elliptic curve, \emph{m} is the message being signed, and \emph{n} is
the size of the elliptic curve. Should an attacker obtain the public key
for a Bitcoin address, however, they could use Shor's algorithm to
mathematically recover the private key associated with that address.

11

\textbf{7.1.2 Ethereum}

Like Bitcoin, Ethereum utilizes the elliptic curve and ECDSA to create
digital signatures for its transactions. Instead of using the public key
of an address as its address on the Ethereum blockchain, Ethereum
calculates the Keccak-256 hash of the public key to form the address of
the account.

