\textbf{7.3} \textbf{Attack Scenarios}

\textbf{7.3.1 Store-Now-Decrypt-Later (SNDL)}

In this type of attack, an attacker harvests the cryptocurrencies made
with blockchain tech-nology, stores them, and decrypts them with the
power of a quantum computer. While not currently possible for such
attacks to occur, the exposure of public keys to the blockchain presents
the potential for such an attack to occur should quantum computers
become avail-able.

\textbf{7.3.2 Direct Key Recovery}

Once an attacker gains access to a quantum computer, those public keys
stored on the blockchain can be directly attacked in order to recover
the private keys associated with those public keys. Estimates suggest
that this type of attack will take between hours and days to execute for
cryptocurrencies with 256-bit keys. Thus, those addresses associated
with public keys will be at risk of having their cryptocurrencies
compromised.

12

\textbf{7.4} \textbf{Economic Impact Assessment}

The total market for Bitcoin is currently valued at \$800 billion. The
market for Ethereum is valued at \$300 billion. The total market value
of all cryptocurrencies is \$2 trillion. The number of public keys
exposed on the blockchain represents 20-30\% of the total supply of
Bitcoin. Furthermore, another estimate suggests that 15-20\% of the
total supply of Bitcoin is represented by addresses associated with
public keys whose private keys are lost or inac-cessible (Satoshi's
coins). Thus, the total value of the cryptocurrencies that are at risk
of being decrypted by quantum computers is between \$100 billion and
\$300 billion.

\textbf{7.5} \textbf{Migration Strategies}

\textbf{7.5.1 Hard Fork}

A hard fork of the blockchain will require the creation of a new version
of the protocol. Such a protocol will require:

\begin{quote}
• New cryptographic algorithm

• New protocol version

• Implementation of a period for the migration of cryptocurrencies from
the old to the new blockchain protocol

• Freezing of the addresses of those who do not participate in the
protocol change
\end{quote}

One of the challenges to implementing such a protocol will be the
decentralized nature of the blockchain. Furthermore, many of the public
keys in use on the blockchain do not have their associated private keys.
Other challenges will be the need to create the new protocol in a way
that is backwards compatible with the existing protocol, as well as to
account for the increased sizes of transactions that will need to be
created under the new cryptographic algorithm.

\textbf{7.5.2 Hybrid Cryptography}

An alternative to creating a hard fork in the blockchain is the
implementation of a hybrid cryptographic system. Such a system will
utilize both classical and post-quantum crypto-graphic algorithms for
the creation of digital signatures. For instance, one blockchain system
can use ECDSA signatures while another uses digital signatures based
upon the Module-LWE problem.

Some of the advantages of a system like this will be that even if the
classical crypto-graphic system is broken, the transactions will still
be secure. Furthermore, the use of the same general processes for the
creation of digital signatures as are currently utilized on the
blockchain means that there will be no need to make changes to the
blockchain itself to implement such a system. Some of the disadvantages
of this system will be the doubling of the size of digital signatures,
as well as the increased length of time required to verify each digital
signature and transaction created under this system.

13

\textbf{8 Implementation Case Study}

\textbf{8.1} \textbf{Post-Quantum Bitcoin Prototype}

\textbf{8.1.1 Design Specifications}

The design of a post-quantum version of Bitcoin will utilize the
CRYSTALS-Dilithium digital signature system, which provides security at
the NIST security level 2. The public keys will be of size 1,312 bytes
(compared to 33 bytes in ECDSA), the digital signatures will be of size
2,420 bytes (compared to 71 bytes in ECDSA), and the time required for
signature verification will be around 200 microseconds (compared to 50
microseconds for ECDSA).

\textbf{8.1.2 Performance Analysis}

Currently, the size of a Bitcoin transaction is around 250 bytes.
Therefore, the size of transactions will increase to 2,600 bytes for the
post-quantum system. Furthermore, the current number of transactions
that can occur within a block is between 2,000 and 2,500. Thus, only
between 200 and 250 transactions will be able to fit within a block for
the post-quantum system.

\textbf{8.1.3 Scalability Solutions}

Some of the possible solutions to the scalability issue of Bitcoin will
be to:

\begin{quote}
• Increase the size of the block

• Implement signature aggregation algorithms

• Develop Layer-2 solutions (like the Lightning network)

• Implement optimized implementations of the post-quantum protocol
\end{quote}

\textbf{8.2} \textbf{Ethereum Post-Quantum Considerations}

\textbf{8.2.1 Smart Contract Implications}

The implications of the shift to digital signatures based upon the
Module-LWE problem will include changes to the way that smart contracts
verify digital signatures of transactions. In addition, the creation of
multi-signature wallets will change. Finally, the gas costs for smart
contracts to verify digital signatures will change. Currently, smart
contracts require around 3,000 units of gas to verify digital
signatures. In contrast, the CRYSTALS-Dilithium digital signature system
will require between 100,000 and 500,000 units of gas for signature
verification.

\textbf{8.2.2 Protocol Upgrades}

The protocol for Ethereum will have to be changed to include smart
contracts that support the new digital signatures. For instance, the
protocol can change its smart contracts to

14

create a type of transaction that uses these new types of digital
signatures. Furthermore, the protocol can change its account abstraction
system (EIP-4337) to handle these new digital signatures. Finally, the
protocol can create new precompiles to speed the verification of these
digital signatures.

\textbf{9 Discussion}

\textbf{9.1} \textbf{Mathematical Foundations}

The main goal of this research was to investigate some of the
differences between classical cryptographic systems and post-quantum
cryptographic systems. As discussed above, classi-cal cryptographic
systems mainly work within the context of cyclic groups (both finite
fields and elliptic curves) and the discrete logarithm problem that
exists within those groups. In contrast, the mathematical framework for
lattice-based cryptographic systems is based upon the
\emph{n}-dimensional Euclidean spaces within which there is no
periodicity to the algorithms.

Another of the main differences between classical cryptographic systems
and lattice-based cryptographic systems is the link between worst-case
and average-case problems for those systems. When using lattice-based
cryptographic systems, an algorithm that is efficient at solving
average-case instances will also be efficient at solving the worst-case
instance of the same problem. However, classical cryptographic systems
rely upon the assumption that problems are difficult to solve on average
but relatively easy to solve in the worst case.

Finally, the reasons that no efficient quantum algorithms have yet been
created for lattice-based cryptographic systems are these mathematical
differences between the systems. For instance, the cyclic groups within
which classical cryptographic systems are based have an inherent
periodicity to their problems, which allows quantum algorithms like
Shor's algo-rithm to efficiently find the period and solve the problem.
The lack of periodicity within lattice problems explains the inability
of current quantum algorithms to efficiently solve those problems.

\textbf{9.2} \textbf{Performance}

One of the main findings of this research is that post-quantum
cryptographic systems are significantly less performant than classical
cryptographic systems. For instance, public keys based upon
quantum-resistant cryptographic systems will be 40-50 times larger than
those created by the ECDSA algorithm for Bitcoin. Additionally, digital
signatures will be 30-40 times larger in size. Furthermore, the
computational costs of using these new systems will be 2-10 times
greater than those of classical cryptographic systems. Despite these
disadvantages, however, the cryptographic systems were still considered
to be acceptable for use due to the existential threat that quantum
computers pose to current cryptographic systems.

\textbf{9.2.1 Implementation Challenges}

Beyond the performance differences between the two types of
cryptographic systems, there are other challenges to the implementation
of these quantum-resistant cryptographic systems to cryptocurrencies
like Bitcoin and Ethereum. Some of these challenges include:

15

\begin{quote}
• Bandwidth requirements for the larger public keys and digital
signatures

• Storage requirements for the blockchain to store the larger digital
transactions

• Increased computational requirements for the blockchain nodes to
verify digital signa- tures

• Backwards compatibility with existing cryptocurrencies
\end{quote}

\textbf{9.3} \textbf{Timeline Urgency}

Given the current rate of development of quantum computers, it will take
between 10 and 30 years for those quantum computers to reach the number
of qubits that will allow them to pose a threat to current cryptographic
systems {[}6{]}. Thus, while it may appear that no action is required in
the present, such action is imperative to take. Should quantum
computers, however, develop at a faster rate than these current
estimates, the urgency to find a solution will be even greater than that
indicated by the 10-30 year estimate.

\textbf{9.4} \textbf{Future Research}

Beyond the research that has already been performed on quantum-resistant
cryptography, there are a few suggestions for future research in this
area. Some of the possible directions for future research in this field
include:

\begin{quote}
• Optimized implementations of the proposed cryptographic systems

• Development of other types of hybrid cryptographic schemes

• Development of techniques to aggregate digital signatures to reduce
the overhead of using the proposed post-quantum cryptographic algorithms

• Exploration of other types of cryptographically hard problems

• Development of quantum-resistant smart contracts
\end{quote}

\textbf{10} \textbf{Conclusion}

This research presents a detailed and comprehensive analysis of the
mathematical reasons that classical cryptographic systems fail against
quantum attacks, while also demonstrating the security of lattice
problems against such quantum attacks. The main mathematical difference
between classical and quantum-resistant systems is the structure of the
problems that are utilized in those systems. While classical
cryptography makes use of cyclic groups that inherently do have periodic
structure that is targeted by quantum algorithms, lattice problems do
not have this same structure.

Furthermore, the fact that breaking the average case of a lattice
problem is equivalent to breaking the worst case of that problem
provides a solid theoretical foundation for the security of these
cryptographic systems.

16

For cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum, such a threat poses both
an existing and imminent danger. As digital signatures that are based on
elliptic curves will be broken by quantum computers within 10 to 30
years, the data and cryptocurrencies of affected users will be at risk
of compromise. Thus, though at the cost of the increased sizes of keys,
digital signatures, and computational costs for those signatures, it is
necessary to implement cryptographic systems that are secure against
quantum computers.

Thus, it is imperative that each of the cryptocurrencies create plans to
implement post-quantum cryptographic systems such as Kyber, Dilithium,
and FALCON. Such plans may include the creation of hybrid cryptographic
systems to provide security for both the classical and the post-quantum
systems. Furthermore, scalability solutions will need to be created to
combat any decrease in the throughput of the blockchains. Finally, it
will also be necessary to create timelines for such an upgrade, as well
as to perform security audits on the proposed systems prior to their
implementation.

Overall, the mathematical foundations of these systems are solid, the
algorithms are standardized, and the threat timeline is clear. Thus, the
blockchain and cryptocurrency communities must take action to ensure the
long-term security of their systems against quantum computers.

